<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1940,2037]" pageId="4" pageNumber="413">
The many morphological differences betWeen the genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1997" box="[837,980,1940,1965]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="413" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Meropathina">Meropathina</taxonomicName>
are discussed and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="4" pageNumber="413" refId="ref2891" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997) Life on the effectiVe bubble: exocrine secretion deliVery systems (ESDS) and the eVolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article">Perkins (1997</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation box="[230,291,1977,2001]" pageId="4" pageNumber="413" refId="ref2944" refString="Perkins, P. D. (2004) A reVision of the Western Australian endemic humicolous beetle genus Tympallopatrum Perkins (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Zootaxa, 672, 1 - 16." type="journal article">2004</bibRefCitation>
). Some of these differences are summarized beloW and presented in the key to genera that folloWs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1940,2037]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,151,392]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="414" pageId="4" pageNumber="413">
Recent unpublished DNA sequence data (I. Ribera, pers. com.) has corroborated the sister group relationships of the 
<taxonomicName box="[232,369,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Ochthebiina">Ochthebiina</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1997" box="[434,580,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Meropathina">Meropathina</taxonomicName>
, Which Were proposed by 
<bibRefCitation box="[898,1068,151,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" refId="ref2891" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997) Life on the effectiVe bubble: exocrine secretion deliVery systems (ESDS) and the eVolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article">Perkins (1997)</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of the hypomeral antennal pocket morphology, and differences in the exocrine secretion delivery systems, among other morphological characters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,151,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">
The antennal club of all members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1997" box="[623,766,260,285]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Meropathina">Meropathina</taxonomicName>
have sensilla interspersed With the hydrofuge setae. These sensilla are usually located near the distal end of the club articles. In members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1901" box="[1135,1269,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Meropathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1135,1269,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Meropathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1289,1375,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1749,1772]" captionTargetBox="[250,1310,483,1695]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[249,1310,482,1695]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. Comparison of the hypomeron, antennal pocket, and posterior border of eye: (10–11) Tympanogaster (s. str.) modulatrix (with anomalous second pair of hypomeral antennal pocket setae), (12–13) Meropathus campbellensis. Structures: (e) periocular exocrine pores, (g) hypomeral antennal pocket setae (h) hydrofuge hypomeron, (i) hypomeral antennal pocket, (k) cupule article of antenna, (n) prosternum, (t) postocular hydrofuge, (V) cerVical sclerite." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1309845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1979" box="[151,323,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,323,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Tympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are not organized into groups, Whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1997" box="[868,1052,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympallopatrum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[868,1052,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Tympallopatrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the sensilla form distinct clusters (
<figureCitation box="[159,295,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–19" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1916,1939]" captionTargetBox="[193,1390,566,1854]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[165,1421,502,1885]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 14–19. Tympallopatrum longitudum: (14) dorsal habitus, (15–16) antenna and prothoracic hypomeron, (17) Venter of head, (18–19) Venter of head, mentum and labrum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1309847/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Figs. 15, 16</figureCitation>
). The antennae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins, 2018" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2018" box="[503,732,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Prototympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[503,732,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Prototympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1979" box="[990,1161,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[990,1161,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Tympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1309845/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" startId="5.[151,264,1749,1772]" targetBox="[250,1310,483,1695]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1749,1864]" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,339,1749,1772]" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">FIGURES 10–13.</emphasis>
Comparison of the hypomeron, antennal pocket, and posterior border of eye: (10–11) 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1979" box="[1205,1361,1751,1772]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tympanogaster</taxonomicName>
(s. str.) modulatrix
</emphasis>
(with anomalous second pair of hypomeral antennal pocket setae), (12–13) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brookes" authorityYear="1951" box="[1041,1313,1780,1802]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Meropathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="campbellensis">
<emphasis box="[1041,1313,1780,1802]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Meropathus campbellensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Structures: (e) periocular exocrine pores, (g) hypomeral antennal pocket setae (h) hydrofuge hypomeron, (i) hypomeral antennal pocket, (k) cupule article of antenna, (n) prosternum, (t) postocular hydrofuge, (V) cerVical sclerite.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1908,2005]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1436,151,392]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="415" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">
The maxilla in members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1979" box="[510,682,1910,1933]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[510,682,1910,1933]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Tympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
provide distinctive, derived features (
<figureCitation box="[1109,1246,1908,1933]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1989,2012]" captionTargetBox="[249,1345,264,1860]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[194,1392,245,1908]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Maxillae of representatiVe members of Meropathina" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1309851/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Figs. 25–28</figureCitation>
). The lacinia has a large, scoop-like, apical tooth in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1979" box="[560,732,1945,1968]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[560,732,1945,1968]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="414">Tympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; in the presumed ancestral condition of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1252,1384,1944,1969]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Ochthebiini">Ochthebiini</taxonomicName>
this structure has a tooth-like shape With a bifid apex (see 
<bibRefCitation box="[751,902,1980,2005]" pageId="5" pageNumber="414" refId="ref2850" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1980) Aquatic beetles of the family Hydraenidae in the Western Hemisphere: classification, biogeography and inferred phylogeny (Insecta: Coleoptera). Quaestiones Entomologicae, 16, 3 - 554." type="journal article">Perkins 1980</bibRefCitation>
: 297). The galea has several closely spaced, flat teeth that together form a palmate shape; this is unique in the family. There is some variation in the length and proportions of the maxillary palpi. This variation, like the variation in leg length, is related to the microhabitat: the strictly aquatic members having longer legs and palpi, and the moss dWelling or humicolous species having shorter legs and palpi. The maxillae of 
<taxonomicName authority="Perkins, 2018" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2018" box="[507,736,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Prototympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis box="[507,736,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">Prototympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[751,833,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–22" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1980,2003]" captionTargetBox="[193,1403,280,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[161,1425,260,1881]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 21–22. Comparison of maxilla and mentum: (21) Prototympanogaster lordhowensis, (22) Meropathus chuni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1309849/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) are similar in morphology to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="1979" box="[1258,1429,261,284]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Tympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1258,1429,261,284]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">Tympanogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the legs are moderately long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">
The mentum of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2018" box="[380,765,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Prototympanogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lordhowensis">
<emphasis box="[380,765,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">Prototympanogaster lordhowensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1901" box="[820,1023,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Meropathus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chuni">
<emphasis box="[820,1023,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">Meropathus chuni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are different in shape and especially chaetotaxy (
<figureCitation box="[287,425,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–22" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1980,2003]" captionTargetBox="[193,1403,280,1838]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[161,1425,260,1881]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 21–22. Comparison of maxilla and mentum: (21) Prototympanogaster lordhowensis, (22) Meropathus chuni." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1309849/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="415">Figs. 21, 22</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
